entry.title: Allow DevTools intercept fetch keepalive requests after migration
entry.content:
1. The Chromium DevTools Protocol allows developer to intercept

network requests by calling `Network.setRequestInterception` [1]

API. This is achieved by intercepting a URLLoaderFactory mojo

by adding a proxy between a remote/receiver pair (See [2]).



However, after in-browser migration, the URLLoaderFactory

implementation used by fetch keepalive requests will not be

the default one for other subresources, such that it cannot be

updated by the browser -> renderer mojo call

`SubresourceLoaderUpdater::UpdateSubresourceLoaderFactories()`.



This CL supports such URLLoaderFactory update from RFHI via

KeepAliveURLLoaderService::FactoryContext, without going back

to renderer.



Example failure without this CL: [3]



2. This CL also fixes the issue that fetch keepalive requests stop

working after network service crashes. The service is also created

via `RenderFrameHostImpl::UpdateSubresourceLoaderFactories()`, which

will be able to update KeepAliveURLLoaderService via its

FactoryContext.



[1]: https://chromedevtools.github.io/devtools-protocol/tot/Network/#method-setRequestInterception

[2]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/devtools/devtools_url_loader_interceptor.cc;l=759;drc=8e78783dc1f7007bad46d657c9f332614e240fd8

[3]: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/linux-rel/1625058/test-results?sortby=&groupby=

entry.title: Add metrics for compose dialog consent flows
entry.content:
This CL logically separates a compose "consent session" from a "main session" for metrics purposes. ComposeSessions begin when a dialog is created. Compose "consent sessions" end when the dialog advances past the consent/disclaimer UI to the main UI state, or when the dialog is closed via close button or rejection of consent.



In the former case, we will log two separate sets of metrics: one for the dialog in its consent UI state, and one for the dialog in its main UI state. In this way we keep logged information about the consent dialog separate from existing metrics.



This CL introduces the following metrics for the above purposes

Compose.Session.DialogShownCountConsent.Accepted and Compose.Session.DialogShownCountConsent.Ignored

- Track the number of shows of the dialog for a compose consent session. Split by whether the session ends "Accepted" (consent was given or disclaimer was acknolwedged) or "Ignored" (consent was denied or x button closed)

Compose.Session.Consent.CloseReason

- The ways in which the consent session is exited. This includes both ending session lifetime by closing the dialog, and ending just the consent portion of the session by advancing to the dialog's main UI state. In the latter case, we also split by whether or not the main session ended with an inserted suggestion.

Compose.Session.Consent.GivenInSession

- As documented

entry.title: Fix the broken tests when AppStorage is enabled(Part 5).
entry.content:
When the kAppServiceStorage flag is enabled, AppService blocks the

app publishers creating until it's ready, after reading from the

AppStorage file. This affects some tests:



1. BorealisContextTest.*.

Because BorealisServiceFake is created when BorealisApps publisher is

created, and tests use BorealisServiceFake which reports CHECK error

due to no BorealisFeatures setting.



2. BorealisInstallUrlHandlerTest.*.

Because BorealisServiceFake is created when BorealisApps publisher is

created, and tests use BorealisServiceFake which reports CHECK error

due to no BorealisWindowManager setting.



2. BorealisShutdownMonitorTest.*.

Because BorealisServiceFake is created when BorealisApps publisher is

created, and tests use BorealisServiceFake which reports CHECK error

due to no BorealisWindowManager setting.



Modify Borealis's tests to set BorealisFeatures, BorealisWindowManager

for BorealisServiceFake in tests.



BUG=1385932, b:307623506

entry.title: Clarify lifetime corner case in OnRenderProcessHostCreated comment
entry.content:
The name of this observer implies that it's called once per RPH, when

said RPH is created. In reality, it can be called multiple times for the

same RPH if that RPH is reused for a different renderer process.



This can be problematic if, for instance, an Observer uses this callback to set itself up as a `RenderProcessHostObserver`. This Observer would attempt to register itself twice if it didn't verify that it wasn't already observing the RPH.



This CL only clarifies the comment for OnRenderProcessHostCreated with

this information.

entry.title: Fix the broken tests when AppStorage is enabled(Part 4).
entry.content:
When the kAppServiceStorage flag is enabled, AppService blocks the

app publishers creating until it's ready, after reading from the

AppStorage file. This affects some tests, e.g.

ChromeHidDelegateRenderFrameTest.*. Those tests crash, because TestingProfileManager's ScopedTestingLocalState setting in

TestingBrowserProcess.



ExtensionAppsChromeOs::Initialize observes policy in pref, which

depends on ScopedTestingLocalState. Well,

TestingBrowserProcess::SetLocalState uses some workaround for

PrefService. So when the test is existing it may cause the error:

Received signal 11 SEGV_ACCERR 5610a0fd0680

#0 0x7fed5d5089cc base::debug::CollectStackTrace()

#1 0x7fed5d4c0a1a base::debug::StackTrace::StackTrace()

#2 0x7fed5d4c09d5 base::debug::StackTrace::StackTrace()

#3 0x7fed5d508388 base::debug::(anonymous namespace)::StackDumpSignalHandler()

#4 0x7fecdb07d510 (/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6+0x3c50f)

#5 0x5610a0fd0680



Modify the test setup process to create the user manager first, then

create the profile to align with the production code in ChromeOS.

entry.title: Make ic-width consistent regardless of text orientation.
entry.content:
We obtained the ic-width using the FontMetrics::IdeographicFullWidth()

function. Unfortunately, this value is influenced by the text's

orientation. When the orientation is vertically upright,

IdeographicFullWidth() provides the vertical advance height of the CJK

water glyph. However, when the orientation is different, it returns the

horizontal width of the water glyph. As per the definition [1], the

ic-width for font-size-adjust should be a consistent value, which is the

horizontal advance width of the CJK water glyph divided by the font

size. This consistency should be maintained regardless of the text's

orientation.



[1] https://www.w3.org/TR/css-fonts-5/#valdef-font-size-adjust-ic-width



Test: external/wpt/css/css-fonts/font-size-adjust-text-orientation.html
